WEBVTT

00:04.922 --> 00:06.631
<i>If you think that you</i>

00:06.632 --> 00:09.300
<i>and the group you came here
with from San Diego,</i>

00:09.301 --> 00:11.345
<i>if you think you folks are happy now,</i>

00:11.971 --> 00:14.348
<i>wait until they open those doors.</i>

00:14.640 --> 00:16.142
<i>A new car!</i>

00:32.783 --> 00:34.159
<i>I hope...</i>

00:34.160 --> 00:37.037
Hey, cutie, you should rotate,
or you're gonna get bedsores.

00:37.038 --> 00:39.749
Hey, I walked to the fridge
and back twice today.

00:39.957 --> 00:42.877
Oh, twice.
Big exercise.

00:43.085 --> 00:44.712
- Mwah!
- So what's on the menu?

00:44.920 --> 00:45.879
Soup, I guess.

00:45.880 --> 00:48.339
I just got back from the clinic
about three minutes ago.

00:48.340 --> 00:50.009
- Ooh, that's a long day.
- Right?

00:50.384 --> 00:51.552
Is that from Talbot's?

00:52.887 --> 00:56.098
No. Uh, it's for Dad.
It feels like a video.

00:57.433 --> 00:59.893
Well, people have been sending things
since <i>The Times</i> article.

00:59.894 --> 01:02.063
Do I need to be worried about
all this fan mail that you're getting?

01:02.730 --> 01:04.355
Well, that depends
how the soup turns out.

01:04.356 --> 01:06.024
That's my guy.

01:06.025 --> 01:09.111
Ew. Are you seriously joking
about having an affair?

01:10.446 --> 01:11.988
Hey, are you gonna watch this
with me later?

01:11.989 --> 01:13.491
It's the Tournament of Champions.

01:16.243 --> 01:17.577
Dad? Dad?

01:18.621 --> 01:20.122
Charlie!

01:20.498 --> 01:22.792
- Charlie!
- Oh.

01:23.667 --> 01:25.711
Oh, no. No, no, no.

01:26.962 --> 01:28.422
You've built your connection.

01:28.881 --> 01:30.424
He knows you can talk
about his ideas,

01:30.758 --> 01:33.343
that you're his equal,
that he made the right call

01:33.344 --> 01:35.428
in asking to speak to you
and only you.

01:35.429 --> 01:36.555
Now turn it.

01:37.348 --> 01:39.307
No more feelings,
no more theories.

01:39.308 --> 01:40.851
Hit him hard with the facts.

01:41.268 --> 01:43.812
He's about to be buried
under a mountain of hard evidence.

01:43.813 --> 01:45.231
Going to trial is suicide.

01:46.023 --> 01:47.857
Control, he's desperate for control.

01:47.858 --> 01:50.026
He thinks going to trial
will give him that control.

01:50.027 --> 01:52.905
Make him understand
that we own the courtroom.

01:53.656 --> 01:56.408
The only thing that gives him wiggle room
is to plead guilty.

02:00.788 --> 02:02.413
He wants the control.

02:03.958 --> 02:05.251
He loves the control.

02:12.758 --> 02:13.884
Here we go.

02:15.177 --> 02:16.387
You can do this, Fitz.

02:26.021 --> 02:28.524
You didn't happen to bring
those stamps, did you?

02:30.442 --> 02:32.026
Do you ever think about
what you leave behind

02:32.027 --> 02:33.237
as you move through this world?

02:34.238 --> 02:35.405
Do you mean as in

02:35.406 --> 02:37.658
"leave your campsite cleaner
than when you found it"?

02:39.243 --> 02:42.954
My dad, he made me join
the Boy Scouts,

02:42.955 --> 02:44.998
thought it might help me make friends.

02:44.999 --> 02:46.958
It didn't.
But it did teach me

02:46.959 --> 02:49.460
to leave my campsite cleaner
than when I found it.

02:49.461 --> 02:50.712
But what does that matter

02:50.713 --> 02:52.881
if the next day,
a logging company comes in

02:52.882 --> 02:54.175
and chops the whole forest down?

02:55.176 --> 02:56.260
I meant it literally--

02:56.760 --> 02:58.011
like all that you leave behind,

02:58.012 --> 03:00.931
like at the Charles Epstein
bombing site.

03:01.515 --> 03:04.643
You know, you hadn't sent
a package in six years,

03:04.977 --> 03:08.062
and then, on June 22, 1993,

03:08.063 --> 03:10.482
man in Tiburon opens
a brown padded envelope, and...

03:14.778 --> 03:16.030
his whole torso is ripped apart.

03:17.489 --> 03:19.992
I think I read about that one
in the newspaper.

03:20.576 --> 03:22.411
- A geneticist, right?
- Yeah.

03:24.788 --> 03:25.873
He had a daughter.

03:27.208 --> 03:29.167
When a man interacts
with the world,

03:29.168 --> 03:30.461
he leaves traces everywhere.

03:31.295 --> 03:32.879
Now, every action,
every step that you took,

03:32.880 --> 03:33.964
you've been shedding clues--

03:34.340 --> 03:36.634
not one, not two,
but hundreds, thousands.

03:37.134 --> 03:39.845
And they have a warehouse
filled with evidence.

03:43.515 --> 03:44.683
This is a trigger switch.

03:46.060 --> 03:49.188
It's precise. It's unique.
It's made by hand.

03:50.064 --> 03:54.151
Forensics found one virtually intact
at the scene.

03:55.486 --> 03:58.072
They found an identical switch
at your cabin.

03:58.364 --> 04:01.575
This is, uh, wire clippings,
springs,

04:02.618 --> 04:04.995
copper pipe,
aluminum scraps--

04:06.247 --> 04:07.248
all matched.

04:09.875 --> 04:11.085
Stamps.

04:12.544 --> 04:15.130
These are stamps
from the Epstein package,

04:16.006 --> 04:17.508
and these are stamps
from your cabin.

04:18.509 --> 04:21.135
You traveled three days
from Lincoln, Montana,

04:21.136 --> 04:23.555
to mail the package
in San Francisco.

04:23.847 --> 04:26.432
You paid cash,
you used disguises,

04:26.433 --> 04:29.269
which was smart,
except, in your cabin,

04:29.270 --> 04:31.397
we found six pairs
of sunglasses,

04:31.730 --> 04:33.440
some fake mustaches,

04:33.857 --> 04:36.652
and then your journal entries
logging your disguises.

04:37.403 --> 04:40.823
This is the chemical components
of the explosive mixture

04:41.573 --> 04:45.035
and, um, the epoxy
that was used in the box,

04:46.078 --> 04:48.539
your typewriter that was used
for the address label,

04:49.790 --> 04:52.834
carbon paper, and a receipt
for the carbon paper.

04:52.835 --> 04:54.461
It just goes on and on,

04:54.628 --> 04:57.630
and, Ted, they have
thousands of pieces of evidence

04:57.631 --> 04:59.299
that can link you to the Unabom,

04:59.300 --> 05:00.592
but they only need one to convict you.

05:01.218 --> 05:03.971
They're gonna bury you
under a mountain of evidence,

05:04.388 --> 05:06.180
and all your autonomy
is gonna go out the window

05:06.181 --> 05:07.308
the first day of trial.

05:10.477 --> 05:11.812
He's looking good.

05:13.188 --> 05:14.064
Now reel him in.

05:15.733 --> 05:17.860
I want you to change the world.

05:18.027 --> 05:20.321
I want you to start a revolution.

05:20.529 --> 05:22.197
But if you fight this...

05:24.033 --> 05:26.410
if you fight this,

05:27.077 --> 05:29.829
you are gonna lose control
of everything in your life.

05:29.830 --> 05:32.623
You're gonna be a helpless cog
in the machine of justice

05:32.624 --> 05:34.752
until they strap you down
in the electric chair.

05:36.295 --> 05:38.213
You have one option.

05:38.964 --> 05:40.257
It's gonna give you
some bargaining power,

05:41.258 --> 05:42.426
but you got only one.

05:44.136 --> 05:45.888
Plead guilty.

05:46.347 --> 05:48.098
All of this is for one bomb.

05:48.390 --> 05:49.767
There were 15 others

05:50.184 --> 05:51.810
that we haven't even talked about.

05:52.686 --> 05:55.522
So trust me. This is all there is.

06:03.572 --> 06:05.157
All right.

06:07.534 --> 06:09.620
If that's my only option, I'll do it.

06:15.918 --> 06:18.045
- That's it, right?
- That's it.

06:19.338 --> 06:20.881
Can I ask you one question?

06:23.384 --> 06:24.885
Anything.

06:26.136 --> 06:27.845
Since you've been so helpful

06:27.846 --> 06:30.223
walking me through
what evidence the FBI has,

06:30.224 --> 06:32.892
I was hoping
you might confirm for me

06:32.893 --> 06:35.228
something I've suspected
for a long time

06:35.229 --> 06:37.189
but could never get
a straight answer to.

06:37.606 --> 06:42.610
But it seems to me that there is
no forensic evidence whatsoever

06:42.611 --> 06:44.654
tying me to these heinous crimes

06:44.655 --> 06:46.365
besides what you found in my cabin.

06:47.157 --> 06:49.201
Yeah, but they got so much
evidence of every type.

06:49.535 --> 06:52.454
Imagine if you could throw out
all that evidence.

06:54.039 --> 06:55.706
There'd be nothing left, right?

06:55.707 --> 06:57.250
Because it's all here on the table.

06:57.251 --> 06:59.128
You just laid it all out
in front of me.

07:01.088 --> 07:02.339
Yeah.

07:03.465 --> 07:07.427
James, do you really
not have any idea

07:07.428 --> 07:08.887
why I brought you here?

07:12.933 --> 07:14.143
Huh.

07:20.065 --> 07:22.651
This is your search warrant.

07:23.652 --> 07:26.279
It's based on
your linguistic analysis.

07:26.280 --> 07:29.366
This is--This is what
got you into my cabin,

07:29.533 --> 07:33.077
and the prosecution's entire case

07:33.078 --> 07:37.541
<i>rests on this one document,
your--your document.</i>

07:37.916 --> 07:39.710
No, what--
what's he doing?

07:40.419 --> 07:42.962
<i>So I thought
we could discuss something</i>

07:42.963 --> 07:45.549
<i>I learned about only recently,
called</i>

07:46.425 --> 07:48.510
fruit of the poisonous tree.

07:49.970 --> 07:52.388
That's the option that
you're neglecting to mention--

07:52.389 --> 07:55.766
the option where I get
all this evidence thrown out

07:55.767 --> 07:57.311
and I walk away a free man.

08:00.105 --> 08:02.732
The only evidence connecting me
to the Unabom attacks

08:02.733 --> 08:04.233
was found inside my cabin.

08:04.234 --> 08:07.695
The only reason the FBI was legally
allowed to search my cabin

08:07.696 --> 08:09.655
was because of
your search warrant,

08:09.656 --> 08:14.160
but if that search warrant
was issued on false pretenses

08:14.161 --> 08:17.038
or based on arguments
that fail to meet the burden of proof,

08:17.039 --> 08:19.749
well, then all the evidence
found at that location

08:19.750 --> 08:21.752
is deemed fruit of the poisonous tree.

08:21.960 --> 08:24.545
It's tainted.
It's inadmissible.

08:24.546 --> 08:25.838
It's got to be thrown out.

08:25.839 --> 08:28.341
So if the search warrant goes,

08:28.342 --> 08:33.305
then all their mountains
of evidence simply...

08:35.349 --> 08:36.600
disappear.

08:39.728 --> 08:41.230
Do you follow?

08:42.147 --> 08:44.525
<i>The whole case depends on
the evidence from the cabin.</i>

08:44.816 --> 08:47.235
The evidence from the cabin
depends on the search warrant,

08:47.236 --> 08:49.988
but the search warrant depends
on this thing called...

08:50.364 --> 08:52.406
forensic linguistics,

08:52.407 --> 08:56.745
which is a field that you just invented,
James R. Fitzgerald.

08:57.329 --> 09:00.039
There is no precedent
in all legal history

09:00.040 --> 09:03.000
for a search warrant
based on linguistic analysis.

09:03.001 --> 09:06.587
So the question I then place
before the court becomes,

09:06.588 --> 09:10.634
do we trust this man as so expert
that we trust his invention?

09:11.677 --> 09:15.179
Where did you get your
formal training in linguistics,

09:15.180 --> 09:17.307
your PhD, your Master's?

09:19.935 --> 09:22.728
As I hear it, the majority of
your law enforcement career

09:22.729 --> 09:25.816
was spent on the graffiti squad
of a small-town police department.

09:26.024 --> 09:27.275
Is that right?

09:27.276 --> 09:30.611
Now, would you say that
this time spent reading graffiti

09:30.612 --> 09:32.406
constitutes your linguistic training?

09:32.864 --> 09:35.324
<i>By the way, we haven't even gotten
to the content of the warrant yet.</i>

09:35.325 --> 09:36.826
- Shit. Shit!
- Oh, God. Oh.

09:36.827 --> 09:39.745
<i>Perhaps I should leave you
with my annotations.</i>

09:39.746 --> 09:41.455
<i>They're quite extensive.</i>

09:41.456 --> 09:42.666
We gotta get him out of there.

09:43.709 --> 09:44.960
I was right.

09:45.377 --> 09:48.713
Mm. Well, it doesn't really matter
if you're right.

09:48.714 --> 09:50.590
It matters if they believe in you.

09:50.591 --> 09:52.091
And if they don't believe in you,

09:52.092 --> 09:55.678
then they can't trust the warrant.
And if they can't trust the warrant,

09:55.679 --> 09:57.639
then I walk out of here.

09:58.056 --> 10:00.558
Interview's over. Stop.
Get him outta here.

10:00.559 --> 10:02.310
<i>Everything you touched is tainted.</i>

10:02.311 --> 10:03.603
<i>You need look no further.</i>

10:03.604 --> 10:05.187
Give me those.
Those notes are privileged.

10:05.188 --> 10:06.732
You are the poisonous tree.

10:07.024 --> 10:09.901
<i>Get him out.
Don't say anything else.</i>

10:12.738 --> 10:14.197
Good chat.

10:39.848 --> 10:42.434
I found one.
I found a mistake.

10:44.269 --> 10:47.688
Paragraph 185,
"As for the negative consequences

10:47.689 --> 10:49.940
"of eliminating industrial society,

10:49.941 --> 10:52.194
well, you can't eat your cake
and have it, too."

10:53.862 --> 10:58.450
"Eat your cake...
and have it, too."

10:59.910 --> 11:01.078
It's backwards.

11:01.620 --> 11:03.455
It's backwards.

11:05.999 --> 11:08.042
Why aren't you cheering?
I found a mistake.

11:08.043 --> 11:10.044
We're looking for mistakes.
I found the first real mistake.

11:10.045 --> 11:12.631
Okay. Cool. But what does it
tell us about the Unabomber?

11:13.423 --> 11:15.175
We're looking for a "wudder," right,

11:16.051 --> 11:18.261
something that tells us who he is,
where he comes from.

11:18.553 --> 11:21.139
Thank you. Thank you for quoting me
telling you what to do.

11:22.057 --> 11:23.433
What crawled up your ass and died?

11:23.975 --> 11:26.687
Ackerman gave us an office
and a team to comb the manifesto.

11:27.270 --> 11:29.563
After two weeks,
we got nothing.

11:29.564 --> 11:30.482
Well, I have something.

11:32.317 --> 11:33.527
Check it out, yo.

11:35.404 --> 11:37.114
Manifesto, paragraph 11.

11:45.539 --> 11:47.415
These aren't mistakes.

11:47.416 --> 11:49.542
Someone calls me a "broad,"
that's a mistake,

11:49.543 --> 11:50.544
one they would not make
a second time.

11:51.211 --> 11:52.586
"Negro" will get your ass kicked.

11:52.587 --> 11:53.714
Ernie, you're a nerd.

11:54.423 --> 11:55.632
Want to test a Negro?

11:55.799 --> 11:57.425
Huh, broad?

11:57.426 --> 11:58.260
Okay.
Let's go with this.

11:59.302 --> 12:01.221
Let's go with it, all right?
What's it telling us?

12:02.556 --> 12:04.224
What's--
Who talks like this?

12:04.516 --> 12:06.267
Mm-hmm.

12:06.268 --> 12:08.103
My dad, Wally,
he talked like this, but...

12:10.522 --> 12:11.732
It's generational.

12:12.816 --> 12:14.233
It's generational.

12:14.234 --> 12:16.194
So no one 30 to 40 years old

12:16.403 --> 12:18.071
would use those words, right?

12:18.530 --> 12:20.282
- Right?
- Correct. So what are we saying?

12:20.699 --> 12:22.616
I don't know.
I don't know. I don't know.

12:22.617 --> 12:24.118
What--what--
what else does it tell us?

12:24.119 --> 12:25.328
Well, well, also,
if he used these words,

12:25.495 --> 12:27.747
then this is a guy who's never
been around black folks...

12:27.748 --> 12:29.039
- Mm-hmm.
- or women.

12:29.040 --> 12:30.416
- There you go.
- And trust me.

12:30.417 --> 12:32.543
When you're pretty much
the only black guy in the UTF,

12:32.544 --> 12:34.754
you get lots of practice
picking up on language clues.

12:34.755 --> 12:37.424
So with that, he wouldn't live
in San Francisco proper, right?

12:38.008 --> 12:40.260
Except every letter and package
was mailed from here.

12:40.427 --> 12:42.220
Ooh.

12:43.889 --> 12:45.265
Okay. All right.

12:45.849 --> 12:48.225
Don't worry about it.
Let's keep playing.

12:48.226 --> 12:49.852
Maybe he does,

12:49.853 --> 12:53.648
'cause he lives in the suburbs
within driving distance.

12:54.232 --> 12:56.233
Yes.
Give me everything.

12:56.234 --> 12:58.986
Give me every language clue
that we have found in the manifesto.

12:58.987 --> 13:01.698
Okay, well, um, "Negro,"
"chick," "broad,"

13:01.990 --> 13:04.074
"eat your cake," though I don't
know where that gets us.

13:04.075 --> 13:05.701
Just keep going.
Go on. Come on.

13:05.702 --> 13:08.162
Uh, the long sentences,
the formal style--

13:08.163 --> 13:09.371
trying to sound smart.

13:09.372 --> 13:11.624
Okay. The variant spellings,
they're--they're not wrong.

13:11.625 --> 13:13.417
They're just unusual,
like "willful" with one L and...

13:13.418 --> 13:15.252
"Analyze" with the S,
not a Z.

13:15.253 --> 13:17.671
Plus the numbered paragraphs,
numbered end notes,

13:17.672 --> 13:20.382
a corrections page,
works-cited pages...

13:20.383 --> 13:22.051
- Okay.
- It's a weird format.

13:22.052 --> 13:23.677
Okay. Okay.
So what does that tell us?

13:23.678 --> 13:24.887
I don't know.
It's formatted weird.

13:24.888 --> 13:25.971
Aw, come on!

13:25.972 --> 13:27.182
Dude, what do you want?

13:27.808 --> 13:29.684
We've been looking for wudder.
There's no wudder.

13:30.060 --> 13:32.312
I mean, it's an awesome idea.
We gave it a shot.

13:32.562 --> 13:34.356
But discretion is
the better part of valor.

13:34.564 --> 13:36.398
I don't want to be
the next stamp guy.

13:36.399 --> 13:39.652
I mean, he's off interviewing
Eugene O'Neill's grandkids' dog walker,

13:39.653 --> 13:41.029
and his career is over

13:41.363 --> 13:43.073
because he didn't know
when to say "uncle."

13:56.169 --> 13:58.421
Maybe we should call in the experts.

14:02.467 --> 14:04.468
Are you going to
the, uh, San Diego thing?

14:04.469 --> 14:06.720
- I'm not going.
- It's a good one.

14:06.721 --> 14:09.598
Thank you all for coming,

14:09.599 --> 14:11.600
for taking the time
to read the manifesto.

14:11.601 --> 14:13.143
You've all been
asked here today

14:13.144 --> 14:15.271
because you were either cited
in the manifesto

14:15.272 --> 14:17.065
or you work in
a related academic field.

14:17.691 --> 14:21.068
Look, I'm just hoping
that you can shed some light

14:21.069 --> 14:22.779
on who the author is
based on what you read.

14:23.238 --> 14:25.281
Are there things
that you recognize

14:25.282 --> 14:27.449
in the ideas,
in the language,

14:27.450 --> 14:29.076
you know, from someone
that you work with,

14:29.077 --> 14:31.787
a colleague
or former student maybe?

14:31.788 --> 14:33.498
If one of my students wrote this,

14:33.999 --> 14:35.499
he'd be out of the program.

14:35.500 --> 14:37.419
There's no way this guy
would pass peer review.

14:37.752 --> 14:39.879
Eh, you could scrape
by writing like this

14:39.880 --> 14:41.506
in the hard sciences maybe.

14:41.756 --> 14:43.008
Oh, please.

14:43.508 --> 14:45.801
The, uh, work coming
out of your department

14:45.802 --> 14:48.137
hasn't been publishable in 20 years.

14:48.138 --> 14:50.264
- Oh, please.
- I actually do have a question.

14:51.308 --> 14:54.393
Excuse me.

14:54.394 --> 14:55.645
Excuse me.

14:56.187 --> 14:58.773
Was there a corrections page
appended to the front?

15:00.984 --> 15:01.818
Yeah.

15:01.985 --> 15:04.528
And is it called "Corrections"
or "Errata"?

15:04.529 --> 15:06.614
Was it in English or Latin?

15:06.615 --> 15:09.408
Leave it to the comparative
linguistics grad student

15:09.409 --> 15:10.952
to focus on what's relevant.

15:11.494 --> 15:13.537
You know, the Unabomber
had one thing right.

15:13.538 --> 15:15.206
Did you all read paragraph 88?

15:16.583 --> 15:19.460
"Some scientific work
has no conceivable relation

15:19.461 --> 15:21.795
to the welfare of the human race,"

15:21.796 --> 15:24.299
comparative linguistics,
for example.

15:25.216 --> 15:28.302
And you think your work is relevant?

15:33.683 --> 15:35.393
Oh, well, listen to the poli-sci...

15:37.896 --> 15:39.189
Time flies
when you're having fun.

15:40.523 --> 15:42.901
So, who do we see
about our per diem?

15:43.360 --> 15:44.527
Front desk.

15:50.492 --> 15:52.953
Fitz, good stuff today?

15:53.912 --> 15:55.497
Fill me in first thing tomorrow.

15:55.956 --> 15:57.165
- Yeah.
- Excuse me.

15:57.666 --> 15:59.500
You can get your per diem
at the front desk.

